WEBVTT

00:01.640 --> 00:06.020
Okay, the tapes are rolling and I believe I see the needles moving.

00:06.280 --> 00:15.040
Okay, since the Siege of Wonder came out, we haven't seen anything, any novels or short

00:15.040 --> 00:15.640
stories either.

00:17.520 --> 00:20.400
We talked about this while ago, but this is for the tape.

00:20.660 --> 00:26.240
Do you plan to do any more writing or have you outgrown that?

00:26.320 --> 00:26.800
Is that gone?

00:27.340 --> 00:34.260
Oh no, gosh, it's like being a Catholic.

00:34.740 --> 00:38.000
You're not, no one has ever, never a Catholic again.

00:38.160 --> 00:40.380
You just don't happen to be doing it at any one time.

00:41.480 --> 00:49.700
I certainly desperately hope to keep writing and put something together, which will be

00:49.700 --> 00:50.540
a good piece of work.

00:51.500 --> 00:58.840
Right now, as I said, the time, I hope I'm becoming also a better lawyer, a more able

00:58.840 --> 01:03.980
attorney, and that means I can do more and I am expected to do more and I want to.

01:04.640 --> 01:07.320
Also, we now have three children instead of two.

01:09.480 --> 01:16.480
That all presents a lot of breaks in the day and a reduction of available time.

01:16.480 --> 01:24.560
It's rather difficult to be turning over a consistent plot line in your mind when somebody

01:24.560 --> 01:28.420
insists just because they're paying you much, much money an hour to think about their problem.

01:29.060 --> 01:33.820
It's kind of difficult to maintain the threat of your character's problems in your mind,

01:33.860 --> 01:37.600
so when you're ready to sit down, you at least have, if you don't know what's going to happen

01:37.600 --> 01:43.580
next, at least you remember what just happened by the same token, organization of children,

01:45.940 --> 01:52.260
things like that, charming little people like that make it kind of difficult to write some

01:52.260 --> 01:55.260
bitter and black stuff that I've done before.

01:59.400 --> 02:03.300
So, time has changed, people have changed, and the environment has changed, and I certainly

02:03.300 --> 02:07.380
have every intention of sticking at it until it comes together again.

02:07.720 --> 02:12.220
I can't really conceive of any time when I just pack up the typewriter forever and say,

02:12.220 --> 02:15.160
that's it for me, there's no more point in all this.

02:17.040 --> 02:21.280
I've never allowed that, I think to come back to something I already mentioned, I've never allowed

02:21.280 --> 02:27.020
the writing, although it has probably been the most important part of my life for a great

02:27.020 --> 02:37.560
many years, in one sense or another, it has never dominated to the extent that I really

02:37.560 --> 02:43.220
had to do a good job, or to the extent that failure in any kind of time frame was to be

02:43.220 --> 02:44.180
a personal disaster.

02:45.320 --> 02:51.440
I remember the biographies of the great writers of the 1930s, and the commitment to those

02:51.440 --> 02:56.580
stuff, and indeed the commitment to great many writers who do what I'd say do it for real,

02:57.500 --> 03:03.240
and boy, even great ones very often come to a pretty sad end.

03:05.220 --> 03:10.340
It's a hard regiment, I'm sure everybody realizes it.

03:14.880 --> 03:19.060
It's a little daunting even now, maybe even especially now.

03:23.620 --> 03:33.180
You mentioned your lawyer and that, oh, okay, I go to science fiction conventions, and there

03:33.180 --> 03:38.760
are not a lot of lawyers there, in fact, there are very few, it just doesn't seem that people

03:38.760 --> 03:40.900
who are into that are into science fiction.

03:41.580 --> 03:48.440
How did your bosses, your peers, the people that you work with at your law firm, how did

03:48.440 --> 03:52.560
they take your, when you published The Siege of Wunder, then knowing what you'd done, how

03:52.560 --> 03:53.340
did they view that?

03:53.460 --> 03:53.820
I'm curious.

03:54.340 --> 03:57.900
Well, they viewed it with a great deal of favor because I bought the drinks for that time.

04:00.240 --> 04:09.640
The law firm I'm with right now has a very good mix of personality and achievements on

04:09.640 --> 04:15.260
field or another, and it happens to be mine, and it's regarded certainly without the least

04:15.260 --> 04:23.740
of the law, but I think what I have to be a little, you know, the firm itself attracts

04:24.400 --> 04:27.800
people with different abilities, perspectives and personalities.

04:29.160 --> 04:35.220
The idea of the New York law firm or the organization where the large law firm, we only have about

04:35.220 --> 04:44.340
20 folks in ours, and as an organization, I think it still cultivates individuality, and

04:44.340 --> 04:45.740
it happens to be evidence of mine.

04:46.140 --> 04:50.520
So it's, gosh, I'm the guy that interviewed him read the books.

04:51.020 --> 04:52.920
They told me they enjoyed it.

04:53.080 --> 04:54.200
Like I said, I was buying.

04:56.060 --> 04:57.700
It fits in very well.

04:57.860 --> 05:03.480
It's not, and again, going back to what I just said, it does not dominate my life.

05:03.500 --> 05:11.140
I've not allowed it to, nor have I sought a situation where it could if I wasn't paying

05:11.140 --> 05:15.900
attention or where I would feel that that would be the thing to do.

05:16.680 --> 05:21.340
So I certainly would be very insulted if anybody called it a hobby or dabbling.

05:21.640 --> 05:28.480
I don't believe it's that, but what I'm in the law firm, I trust I'm regarded as a lawyer

05:29.140 --> 05:36.840
who has written some books rather than a writer who does his for living right now.

05:38.020 --> 05:46.640
Do you actively or just somewhat keep up with fantasy and science fiction in its current state now?

05:47.140 --> 05:48.040
Regrettably not.

05:48.460 --> 05:50.720
No, I'm a very slow reader.

05:51.340 --> 05:53.060
I just don't have enough time.

05:57.080 --> 06:05.940
My primary reading category has always been history, still is, but I'm just trying to read

06:05.940 --> 06:10.300
as much as I possibly can of whatever curiosity interests me rather.

06:11.280 --> 06:20.980
So I try to mix it in with a pretty fair cross-section of, I don't want to say popular science,

06:21.180 --> 06:27.100
but a comprehensible science, history, novels, magazines, that sort of thing.

06:27.380 --> 06:30.660
I still read as much as I can, but it's not a great deal.

06:31.180 --> 06:32.840
Not as much nearly as much as I'd like.

06:32.840 --> 06:45.040
And of course what's happening in science fiction, I've really been out of that as much as I was ever truly in it for quite some time.

06:45.320 --> 06:52.700
So as far as the latest, latest, Asia in plot or aspect, I really couldn't help you there.

06:53.360 --> 07:03.740
I just along with the science fiction writers association for a while went to a little minor convention here during an argument.

07:06.100 --> 07:09.200
That was about it, really. Not an argument, man.

07:14.160 --> 07:22.760
Have you ever considered, if you do, write science fiction again, maybe combining your legal mind with the future anyway,

07:22.940 --> 07:26.340
maybe not science fiction, but the future? There's not been much of that done.

07:26.860 --> 07:34.740
Well, I hate to say it, but on the latest attempt on the book that I'm trying to do now, I've really broken myself down.

07:34.740 --> 07:42.960
I'm trying to get away from what I've done. I realize there's very often only a very few kinds of characters that I have in the prior four books.

07:43.880 --> 07:49.700
And the latest one, I'm trying to make the guy a little more of a positive personality.

07:50.300 --> 07:55.700
And as it's turned out, at least in the latest beginning, the fellow attorney general of the United States.

07:56.120 --> 08:02.640
So I guess that means something. I'm a little embarrassed by it, but it's something different.

08:04.260 --> 08:07.660
At least he's the attorney general of what's left of the United States.

08:09.520 --> 08:11.560
Have you ever read any books by Charles Harness?

08:12.700 --> 08:13.380
Yeah, I haven't.

08:13.560 --> 08:21.520
Okay. He's a patent lawyer, and he's one of my very favorite. He's one of these, another one of these people that produces a lot of books.

08:21.620 --> 08:23.840
He's produced six now, and he's about 65.

08:24.180 --> 08:27.980
But he has one that just came out called the Venetian Court, which is from a short story.

08:27.980 --> 08:38.680
I think it's about, I think it's in the near future, whenever if you violate a patent, or if you go around something that's patented and you do it anyway,

08:38.920 --> 08:42.840
that you get the death penalty and the lawyer argues the case.

08:43.580 --> 08:47.240
And he writes, he has some short stories that are pretty interesting about lawyers.

08:47.940 --> 08:54.560
And other than that, I don't think there's any other, there are very few lawyer protagonists or lawyer situations in science fiction.

08:54.560 --> 09:03.880
I really, none spring to mind that in my experience, that the guy, by the way, in this latest story, even though he is a lawyer or an attorney general,

09:04.420 --> 09:13.100
it's not going to be a law of story. He's going to have that position as much for symbolistic purposes as anything else.

09:15.400 --> 09:22.920
But it's not going to be real, what we do, courtroom battle in the past, future, or side time.

09:24.160 --> 09:30.380
If that may be an area, the last thing I want to get into is coming over from the law and writing to the court.

09:31.500 --> 09:35.260
I'm also afraid I just might get into second defending prostrations again, too.

09:35.500 --> 09:37.100
I'm not sure I could do that, especially.

09:40.020 --> 09:44.100
Okay, that's the end of my question list, so I'll turn the tapes off.

09:45.040 --> 09:50.580
I want to ask you just a couple of things off the cuff. When you were in law, you went to New York University.

09:50.720 --> 09:54.340
Where did you live? Did you live right by the University, right on Washington Square?

09:54.560 --> 09:55.900
Right on Washington Square.

09:56.200 --> 10:02.800
Well, I stayed, I had friends that lived in the village on 4th Street right there, just that side of 6th Avenue.

10:02.800 --> 10:07.380
We stayed there part of one summer and really had a great time.

10:08.440 --> 10:12.960
Well, it's a weird neighborhood as you recall. When were you there?

10:13.280 --> 10:16.280
This would have been the summer of 1976.

10:17.220 --> 10:19.920
Okay, well I was there from 1968 to 1971.

10:23.660 --> 10:29.300
The problem, of course, being in school is you got a lot to do. You don't have much money, even if you did have the time.

10:30.080 --> 10:34.800
And the law school itself is pretty much a closed little society. A lot of folks commute it.

10:38.120 --> 10:39.400
You're sure the tape isn't on?

10:39.820 --> 10:41.220
Yeah, no problem.

10:41.720 --> 10:43.240
Real dull bunch of people.

10:47.940 --> 10:56.300
Real, very much interested in Wall Street or Wall Street or Righteousness, hopefully combining the two.

10:56.300 --> 10:57.500
I don't know how they're going to do that.

10:58.180 --> 11:01.300
I was in a very good scholarship group, so I was fortunate in that aspect.

11:01.460 --> 11:04.220
I had some people I got along with.

11:04.580 --> 11:09.620
But, you know, it also had the classic New York syndrome, the world end at the Hudson River.

11:10.320 --> 11:14.500
Maybe to stand high enough, you can see the John Hancock, Karen Chicago and Golden Gate Bridge.

11:14.740 --> 11:16.520
And of course, everybody knows there's nothing in between.

11:17.700 --> 11:18.580
Very provincial.

11:20.460 --> 11:25.980
So that's, you know, there's a lot of good stuff around there, a lot of very exciting stuff.

11:26.180 --> 11:31.500
But as far as my day-to-day environment, pretty discouraging at all.

11:32.360 --> 11:37.040
I have a friend who went, she was, she's my age.

11:39.540 --> 11:44.220
She's a Columbia religion undergraduate.

11:44.980 --> 11:48.500
And then she messed around her husband with the grad school and all.

11:48.560 --> 11:49.340
He's a psych prof.

11:49.860 --> 11:52.820
And she's now in her third year at the University of Texas Law School.

11:53.240 --> 11:57.860
And it's been real interesting to see her, to see how she has changed because of law school.

11:58.000 --> 11:58.840
And she knows it.

11:59.200 --> 12:01.260
And just getting in that mindset.

12:01.760 --> 12:07.740
And I think her assessment of some of the people that was pretty dull, I think that's pretty true, by and large.

12:08.160 --> 12:08.760
Yeah, it is.

12:08.940 --> 12:12.880
And I'll tell you, the change in thinking, here's so much about thinking like a lawyer.

12:12.880 --> 12:14.580
It's not that much of a change.

12:14.920 --> 12:19.120
It becomes a little bit of a change because it's surrounded by the secret language.

12:19.320 --> 12:24.560
You know, you're picking up a couple of Captain Midnight words, nobody else, you know, the guy on the street doesn't know.

12:25.320 --> 12:30.180
You're learning things between you think about it, aren't terribly complicated, but by the same second they're a little artificial.

12:31.340 --> 12:37.660
So that, again, is unique because the average show doesn't know it.

12:37.740 --> 12:39.280
So you know something he doesn't.

12:39.280 --> 12:49.080
And as far as the techniques of thinking go, gee, the only real trick is just to think very carefully, logically and analytically.

12:49.560 --> 12:55.580
And if you do that, you know, and start with first things first, I mean, that's the great secret.

12:56.660 --> 13:06.940
As far as the business of the Socratic Method in class, you know, thinking like a lawyer, I really think it's considerably overblown.

13:08.860 --> 13:11.900
But don't tell her I may be wrong or if I'm right, that's what the maker said.

